THIS FILM IS BASED ON A TRUE STORY

4
00:02:27.020 --> 00:02:32.020
IN MEMORY OF LISA, 
MARTIN AND CORALIE

5
00:02:53.420 --> 00:02:55.630
- Yes, hello.
- Hello.


6
00:03:13.560 --> 00:03:18.320
I heard back from the Public Curator,
and there's nothing we can do.


7
00:03:18.360 --> 00:03:22.070
You can't invest the girl's inheritance
in an income property.


8
00:03:23.400 --> 00:03:25.990
As the estate's only trustee,

9
00:03:26.030 --> 00:03:29.540
you enter into
a certain category of investor.


10
00:03:29.580 --> 00:03:33.960
They don't think real estate
is safe enough.


11
00:03:35.710 --> 00:03:37.670
Not safe enough?

12
00:03:38.710 --> 00:03:41.710
An income property
is the best possible investment.


13
00:03:42.420 --> 00:03:45.300
If you maintain it properly,
it never loses value.


14
00:03:45.340 --> 00:03:48.970
Sure, but you're not a young man anymore.

15
00:03:49.970 --> 00:03:51.850
There's always a risk.

16
00:03:51.890 --> 00:03:55.060
It's $190,000, Mr. Trudel.

17
00:03:55.100 --> 00:03:59.070
The state wants to ensure the inheritance
is safe and can yield a profit.


18
00:04:00.440 --> 00:04:01.900
Anyway…

19
00:04:02.990 --> 00:04:06.200
a financial investment
won't mean anything to Léa.


20
00:04:07.870 --> 00:04:12.660
I'm as disappointed as you are,
but the authorities won't budge.


21
00:04:15.080 --> 00:04:17.790
If I were you,
I'd invest in a fund,


22
00:04:17.830 --> 00:04:22.210
a stable, trustworthy investment fund
with a strong return.


23
00:04:24.170 --> 00:04:28.090
Hang on. I might have something for you.

24
00:04:39.980 --> 00:04:42.570
<i>The fund was created to ensure</i>

25
00:04:42.610 --> 00:04:46.820
that savings stay in Quebec,
in funds managed here.


26
00:04:46.860 --> 00:04:49.780
There's even a component
called the Quebec Fund


27
00:04:49.820 --> 00:04:52.870
that invests exclusively
in local businesses.


28
00:04:52.910 --> 00:04:56.790
Also, the fund is managed
by the Caisse de dépôt et placement,


29
00:04:56.830 --> 00:04:59.540
so it's 100% safe.

30
00:04:59.580 --> 00:05:01.040
I think it's the best option.

31
00:05:01.090 --> 00:05:03.920
To consolidate your savings
and reduce management fees,


32
00:05:03.960 --> 00:05:05.630
I'd strongly recommend it.

33
00:05:05.670 --> 00:05:07.930
Wait until you see the historical returns.

34
00:05:21.650 --> 00:05:24.860
EVOLUTION FUND

35
00:06:10.410 --> 00:06:11.660
What's his story?

36
00:06:11.700 --> 00:06:14.120
He worked at the Caisse
for a couple years.


37
00:06:14.160 --> 00:06:15.990
$500,000 in Maxima Capital?

38
00:06:16.040 --> 00:06:17.250
MONTREAL, SUMMER 2001

39
00:06:17.290 --> 00:06:19.500
- Where did they get the money?
- No idea. We'll ask him.


40
00:06:19.540 --> 00:06:20.920
His company… I forget the name.

41
00:06:20.960 --> 00:06:22.000
Norbourg.

42
00:06:22.040 --> 00:06:25.840
They just requested approval
for a range of new investment funds.


43
00:06:25.880 --> 00:06:27.170
We'll have to meet him.

44
00:06:27.210 --> 00:06:29.286
QUEBEC SECURITIES COMMISSION

45
00:06:31.930 --> 00:06:33.300
Take care of it, will you?

46
00:06:35.850 --> 00:06:38.850
That's not the issue.
Your project is admissible.


47
00:06:38.890 --> 00:06:41.940
I hope so.
We've been working on it for a year.


48
00:06:43.100 --> 00:06:46.770
The problem is your involvement
with Maxima.


49
00:06:48.280 --> 00:06:52.530
The firm has had multiple irregularities
over the past few years.


50
00:06:52.570 --> 00:06:56.330
I'm sure you can understand
that my boss is getting fed up.


51
00:06:56.990 --> 00:07:01.330
Listen, Mr. Asselin,
we believe in Maxima.


52
00:07:01.566 --> 00:07:03.120
We have a recovery plan.

53
00:07:03.170 --> 00:07:05.710
We're serious about
the acquisition process.


54
00:07:07.050 --> 00:07:10.720
I can see that,
with the loan you gave them.


55
00:07:12.680 --> 00:07:14.550
And where did you get that?

56
00:07:15.140 --> 00:07:18.350
We were pretty surprised
when we saw the amount.


57
00:07:18.390 --> 00:07:21.100
I don't have to reveal
my sources of funding.


58
00:07:21.140 --> 00:07:24.600
I'm not obligated,
and you can't presume it's illegal.


59
00:07:26.270 --> 00:07:30.190
I made some money speculating
on the drop in Nortel stock,


60
00:07:30.230 --> 00:07:31.740
when it was at $160.

61
00:07:31.780 --> 00:07:35.110
And I have friends
who help me in my activities.


62
00:07:36.740 --> 00:07:38.740
I'll need more than that.

63
00:07:42.120 --> 00:07:45.960
So you're telling me
the money Norbourg put into Maxima


64
00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:48.750
will hinder the approval
of our funds, right?


65
00:07:48.800 --> 00:07:50.880
With the $200,000 fine my boss gave them

66
00:07:50.920 --> 00:07:53.260
and the suspension
of most of their leadership,


67
00:07:53.300 --> 00:07:54.970
Maxima is foul ball.

68
00:07:55.680 --> 00:07:58.140
It's two completely different things.

69
00:07:58.180 --> 00:08:01.220
Listen, I'll tell it like it is:

70
00:08:01.270 --> 00:08:04.770
If you don't provide documentation
on the source of funding,


71
00:08:04.810 --> 00:08:08.440
the Commission will refuse
to authorize the Maxima transaction


72
00:08:08.480 --> 00:08:10.610
and your funds won't even be considered.

73
00:08:12.070 --> 00:08:13.530
OK, well…

74
00:08:14.320 --> 00:08:16.450
What am I supposed to do with that?

75
00:08:19.530 --> 00:08:22.790
I'll propose a way to move things along.

76
00:08:24.960 --> 00:08:26.870
Don't buy Maxima,

77
00:08:27.380 --> 00:08:30.300
and maybe I can help you
with the mutual funds.


78
00:08:33.300 --> 00:08:35.550
No guarantee. We'll look into it.

79
00:09:30.360 --> 00:09:34.230
With your preventive leave,
we're at one and a half salaries.


80
00:09:34.280 --> 00:09:37.740
I know, Éric, but we always said
we'd buy before having kids.


81
00:09:37.780 --> 00:09:39.110
I know.

82
00:09:40.700 --> 00:09:44.160
There's room for a baby here.
It's not so bad.


83
00:09:49.710 --> 00:09:52.170
How did he get my number?

84
00:09:52.840 --> 00:09:54.420
Who, your mistress?

85
00:09:55.550 --> 00:09:56.800
Don't start, OK?

86
00:09:59.590 --> 00:10:01.470
Tell him I said hi.

87
00:10:05.930 --> 00:10:09.440
Yeah, I know.
I didn't have time to call you back.


88
00:10:09.480 --> 00:10:11.480
Couldn't it wait till Monday?

89
00:10:11.520 --> 00:10:15.020
I'm running out of time.
The 31st is in ten days.


90
00:10:15.610 --> 00:10:18.360
Yeah, I know what day it is.

91
00:10:19.610 --> 00:10:21.280
<i>As I'm sure you're aware,</i>

92
00:10:21.320 --> 00:10:23.570
we're entitled to a 50% tax credit.

93
00:10:23.620 --> 00:10:26.540
But if the funds aren't registered
by the end of the month,


94
00:10:26.580 --> 00:10:28.290
we're closing shop.

95
00:10:28.870 --> 00:10:30.620
Don't make me cry.

96
00:10:30.670 --> 00:10:34.630
I lost $500,000 because of your issue
with Maxima Capital.


97
00:10:34.670 --> 00:10:38.300
I feel like you could
help me get the funds approved.


98
00:10:39.050 --> 00:10:41.090
I don't owe you anything.

99
00:10:42.050 --> 00:10:43.260
<i>Look, Éric,</i>

100
00:10:44.100 --> 00:10:46.680
I know it means extra work for you.

101
00:10:46.720 --> 00:10:49.640
And I know that work
should be compensated.


102
00:11:07.080 --> 00:11:09.500
How much compensation are we talking about?

103
00:11:10.500 --> 00:11:12.170
What did you mean?

104
00:11:14.210 --> 00:11:15.710
What do you think?

105
00:11:20.010 --> 00:11:21.380
$10,000?

106
00:11:22.430 --> 00:11:23.720
Cash.

107
00:11:33.770 --> 00:11:37.190
Look, I'm going on vacation
down south on Thursday.


108
00:11:37.230 --> 00:11:41.530
I'll give you $5,000 before leaving
and the rest when I get back.


109
00:11:41.570 --> 00:11:43.450
If the funds are approved.

110
00:11:53.620 --> 00:11:57.460
For example, in January '98,

111
00:11:57.500 --> 00:11:59.170
there's a big difference.

112
00:12:00.340 --> 00:12:05.640
And in the CITR financial statements,
there are errors in the trial balance.


113
00:12:05.680 --> 00:12:07.430
Can't you get Josianne to do it?

114
00:12:07.470 --> 00:12:10.470
No, I'd prefer if you did it.
It's not just the summaries.


115
00:12:10.520 --> 00:12:12.560
We'll have to look through the documents.

116
00:12:12.600 --> 00:12:15.440
OK, give me the file.
I'll see what I can do.


117
00:12:15.980 --> 00:12:17.900
Don't look too excited!

118
00:12:17.940 --> 00:12:19.570
It's just so fun.

119
00:12:23.280 --> 00:12:26.070
Réné, you'll finish
the week with Maxima, OK?


120
00:12:26.110 --> 00:12:27.950
I'll send you my research.

121
00:12:54.180 --> 00:12:56.310
INVESTIGATOR

122
00:12:57.980 --> 00:13:00.480
- That stays at the front, guys.
- No problem.


123
00:13:00.520 --> 00:13:03.230
That box goes in
the back room with IT.

124
00:13:03.570 --> 00:13:04.650
Vince!

125
00:13:08.490 --> 00:13:10.780
I'll hang my licences here,

126
00:13:10.830 --> 00:13:14.160
and our logo at the entrance
in big letters.


127
00:13:14.200 --> 00:13:16.710
Jesus, how much are
these offices costing you?


128
00:13:16.750 --> 00:13:20.670
That's how it works, Carl.
To get rich, you have to look rich.


129
00:13:21.170 --> 00:13:22.250
Excuse me, Vincent.

130
00:13:22.300 --> 00:13:26.090
I have Éric Asselin, the investigator
from the Commission on the line for you.


131
00:13:26.130 --> 00:13:27.430
It sounds urgent.

132
00:13:29.430 --> 00:13:30.720
I'll take it.

133
00:13:32.100 --> 00:13:33.350
Shut the door, Carl.

134
00:13:33.390 --> 00:13:34.770
Yes.

135
00:13:40.770 --> 00:13:42.020
Hello?

136
00:13:53.700 --> 00:13:55.290
Hey, neighbor!

137
00:13:55.750 --> 00:13:58.370
We're right next door now, corner of Union.

138
00:13:59.170 --> 00:14:00.710
Thanks.

139
00:14:02.040 --> 00:14:05.510
Yeah, business is good.

140
00:14:06.090 --> 00:14:08.090
New downtown offices.

141
00:14:08.760 --> 00:14:10.130
Very good, even.

142
00:14:10.180 --> 00:14:14.140
Desjardins, via the Opvest branch,
gave us a large management mandate.


143
00:14:14.180 --> 00:14:15.720
It's given us a real boost.

144
00:14:15.770 --> 00:14:18.690
Listen, Vincent,
I don't have a lot of time,


145
00:14:18.730 --> 00:14:20.560
and I shouldn't be doing this…

146
00:14:21.400 --> 00:14:23.520
but there's something you should know.

147
00:14:24.070 --> 00:14:28.190
Your little ventures over the past months
have attracted a lot of attention.


148
00:14:28.740 --> 00:14:30.280
We'll be asking for documents,

149
00:14:30.320 --> 00:14:33.910
and I strongly advise you
to answer our questions properly.


150
00:14:33.950 --> 00:14:36.410
We haven't gotten a subpoena or anything.

151
00:14:36.450 --> 00:14:39.540
You could say the investigation
is still unofficial.


152
00:14:40.330 --> 00:14:42.210
My boss called the shot.

153
00:14:43.880 --> 00:14:46.170
Guess who's leading the investigation.

154
00:16:04.870 --> 00:16:07.170
Someone wants to try the car.

155
00:16:27.440 --> 00:16:29.480
Could you pass me the rag?

156
00:16:35.490 --> 00:16:37.030
Thanks.

157
00:16:39.910 --> 00:16:41.370
I'm sorry.

158
00:16:51.050 --> 00:16:55.260
So the serial number you see here
is on each unit,


159
00:16:55.300 --> 00:16:57.390
but often at the back of the machine.

160
00:16:57.430 --> 00:17:00.560
You have to pull it out
to see it, unfortunately.


161
00:17:00.600 --> 00:17:04.100
But if the serial number
doesn't match the one declared,


162
00:17:04.140 --> 00:17:07.940
that means the ATM
has probably been hacked.


163
00:17:07.980 --> 00:17:11.320
So it's important to write down the number.

164
00:17:12.690 --> 00:17:13.780
OK.

165
00:17:15.240 --> 00:17:17.900
We have to be vigilant.
There are a lot.


166
00:17:17.950 --> 00:17:21.490
Right, Guy? How many did we find
in Greater Montreal?


167
00:18:08.620 --> 00:18:11.750
Your guest is waiting at the usual table.

168
00:18:16.710 --> 00:18:18.260
Thank you, Mélissa.

169
00:18:18.760 --> 00:18:20.010
Hello!

170
00:18:25.890 --> 00:18:28.430
We spend our days
talking about you at work.


171
00:18:28.480 --> 00:18:30.650
Might as well talk about you at night.

172
00:18:31.600 --> 00:18:33.690
Not all bad things, I hope.

173
00:18:33.730 --> 00:18:35.400
That's confidential.

174
00:18:38.030 --> 00:18:40.860
But I'm hearing a lot of things.

175
00:18:42.620 --> 00:18:45.330
I even heard you're looking
for a VP of finance.


176
00:18:46.620 --> 00:18:50.250
Oh yeah? You don't miss much.

177
00:18:51.210 --> 00:18:52.250
It's true.

178
00:18:52.290 --> 00:18:54.380
I need a VP of finance

179
00:18:54.420 --> 00:18:58.050
to create Norbourg's securities division,
among other things.


180
00:18:58.090 --> 00:19:01.260
I'd also like to
get into the European game.


181
00:19:02.970 --> 00:19:07.180
Well, listen, I might know someone.

182
00:19:08.100 --> 00:19:10.810
Someone with all the qualifications,

183
00:19:11.440 --> 00:19:14.480
with experience as an investigator
at the Commission.


184
00:19:15.730 --> 00:19:17.190
Interesting…

185
00:19:18.900 --> 00:19:23.950
Such a person could certainly be useful,

186
00:19:23.990 --> 00:19:28.830
if ever the Commission started
sticking their nose in our business.


187
00:19:30.160 --> 00:19:32.210
He knows all about audits.

188
00:19:32.920 --> 00:19:37.500
He was a tax auditor for three years,
and he's been an investigator for four.


189
00:19:38.500 --> 00:19:42.220
This guy could definitely help you.
It'd be easy for him, even.


190
00:19:43.010 --> 00:19:47.640
But… he'll want to be
compensated accordingly.


191
00:19:50.430 --> 00:19:51.520
And…

192
00:19:52.020 --> 00:19:56.150
why does this person
want to quit his job?

193
00:19:58.150 --> 00:20:00.230
Vincent, I'll be straight with you.

194
00:20:00.740 --> 00:20:04.073
This person spends his days
looking at your salaries.


195
00:20:04.240 --> 00:20:06.820
He knows how much they make
on the other side.


196
00:20:08.280 --> 00:20:09.700
Well then…

197
00:20:10.750 --> 00:20:13.960
maybe this person and I should meet.

198
00:20:15.500 --> 00:20:18.000
In the meantime, let's drink to his health.

199
00:20:28.810 --> 00:20:30.970
No way we're waiting. Watch.

200
00:20:36.560 --> 00:20:39.110
Good night? Thanks.

201
00:20:47.120 --> 00:20:48.320
How did you swing that?

202
00:20:48.370 --> 00:20:50.910
You know someone
at the Ministry of Finance?


203
00:20:50.950 --> 00:20:53.290
A guy I went to university with.

204
00:20:53.330 --> 00:20:54.580
He approached you?

205
00:20:54.620 --> 00:20:57.920
No, we ran into each other last year
in Quebec City.


206
00:20:57.960 --> 00:21:01.710
I was at the investment trade fair
with my cousin.


207
00:21:02.420 --> 00:21:03.970
<i>I hadn't seen him in a decade.</i>

208
00:21:04.010 --> 00:21:06.220
<i>I didn't even know
he was at the Ministry.</i>


209
00:21:13.430 --> 00:21:15.520
Well, well!

210
00:21:17.730 --> 00:21:19.400
How's it going, chief?

211
00:21:19.440 --> 00:21:21.730
Man! I can't believe it!

212
00:21:21.770 --> 00:21:23.900
Come here. Long time no see, big guy!

213
00:21:23.940 --> 00:21:26.460
- What are you doing here?
- What are <i>you</i>doing here?


214
00:21:26.526 --> 00:21:28.780
Tell you later.
Carl Bilodeau, my cousin.


215
00:21:28.820 --> 00:21:31.700
- I'm Yan.
- Yan Raymond. We went to school together.


216
00:21:31.740 --> 00:21:34.120
- There's a few stories there.
- I can imagine.


217
00:21:35.410 --> 00:21:37.370
You're finding out before anyone.

218
00:21:38.710 --> 00:21:43.590
I'm telling you because promoting
these programs is part of my job.


219
00:21:43.630 --> 00:21:45.970
I'm definitely interested.

220
00:21:46.760 --> 00:21:48.380
I didn't know about that.

221
00:21:49.340 --> 00:21:50.760
No, it's brand new.

222
00:21:51.640 --> 00:21:54.220
"Political will," you might say.

223
00:21:57.980 --> 00:22:03.070
Anyway, there's a huge tax credit
if you start new mutual funds this year.


224
00:22:09.070 --> 00:22:11.726
<i>We crossed paths
a couple times after that.</i>


225
00:22:12.240 --> 00:22:14.290
<i>He came to help us out.</i>

226
00:22:15.750 --> 00:22:17.750
There's money to be made, Vince.

227
00:22:18.460 --> 00:22:21.080
But you gotta know how to get it.

228
00:22:23.590 --> 00:22:25.050
Guess what?

229
00:22:26.630 --> 00:22:28.300
Turns out I know how.

230
00:22:31.390 --> 00:22:34.560
This isn't the best place
to talk about it, though.


231
00:22:36.430 --> 00:22:37.810
How much do you want?

232
00:23:03.000 --> 00:23:07.420
<i>Four or five months later,
we were on the brink of bankruptcy.</i>


233
00:23:11.180 --> 00:23:14.220
Vincent, it just arrived.

234
00:23:19.180 --> 00:23:21.560
It worked? We got it?

235
00:23:22.650 --> 00:23:24.440
We got the tax credit?

236
00:23:26.150 --> 00:23:28.860
One fucking million, from the government!

237
00:23:38.950 --> 00:23:42.580
Yeah. Nice to have old college pals.

238
00:23:42.620 --> 00:23:47.380
It wasn't a gift, though.
More like the other way around.


239
00:24:19.580 --> 00:24:20.790
Thank you.

240
00:24:24.620 --> 00:24:27.670
Where did you get funds before?

241
00:24:27.710 --> 00:24:31.210
We were fucking around
in investment clubs.


242
00:24:31.970 --> 00:24:35.470
You know, it's hard to get started

243
00:24:35.510 --> 00:24:39.510
with no backers or trust fund.

244
00:24:41.470 --> 00:24:43.140
I got fed up.

245
00:24:44.140 --> 00:24:46.350
I switched strategies.

246
00:24:48.690 --> 00:24:51.480
That was about six months ago.

247
00:24:51.530 --> 00:24:54.650
It was Friday afternoon.
I was alone in the office.


248
00:24:54.700 --> 00:24:58.700
<i>I told you about the Desjardins
management mandate, the Opvest funds.</i>


249
00:24:58.740 --> 00:25:00.660
<i>Yeah, the $20 million.</i>

250
00:25:17.590 --> 00:25:20.100
Yes, is this Investpro TD?

251
00:25:21.140 --> 00:25:24.390
Yes, I'd like to make a withdrawal.

252
00:25:26.100 --> 00:25:29.150
Yes, Norbourg, Vincent Lacroix.
I'm the president.


253
00:25:30.650 --> 00:25:33.280
January 11, 1967.

254
00:25:34.740 --> 00:25:39.820
Yes, a $150,000 withdrawal
from the Opvest RT1 account.


255
00:25:41.580 --> 00:25:46.460
Yes, I want to do a simulation
to test a new model.


256
00:25:46.500 --> 00:25:50.340
Sort of a research and development thing.

257
00:25:50.790 --> 00:25:53.630
Just to make sure everything
performs as expected.


258
00:25:54.210 --> 00:25:56.420
I had an ironclad explanation.

259
00:25:56.470 --> 00:25:59.180
I thought I'd have to tell him
my life story.


260
00:25:59.220 --> 00:26:00.600
But not at all.

261
00:26:00.640 --> 00:26:03.560
They transferred the cash,
no questions asked.


262
00:26:05.600 --> 00:26:08.940
Yes, in the National Bank Norbourg account.

263
00:26:08.980 --> 00:26:12.570
The number is… Sorry.

264
00:26:12.610 --> 00:26:16.360
It's 2364292.

265
00:26:16.400 --> 00:26:18.860
Transit: 76451.

266
00:26:22.990 --> 00:26:25.160
No, thank you. 
That'll be all.

267
00:26:25.200 --> 00:26:26.580
Thank you.

268
00:26:38.800 --> 00:26:40.180
I don't understand.

269
00:26:40.220 --> 00:26:43.550
You deposit the money
in the Norbourg account directly?


270
00:26:44.350 --> 00:26:47.270
No, we put the money back.
No one is the wiser.


271
00:26:47.310 --> 00:26:49.390
It's just to unblock capital.

272
00:26:51.020 --> 00:26:52.270
You know, Éric,

273
00:26:52.310 --> 00:26:57.070
to move forward,
get bigger and stronger,


274
00:26:57.110 --> 00:26:59.530
we have no choice but to gamble.

275
00:26:59.570 --> 00:27:02.740
You put it back
or you're going to put it back?


276
00:27:06.200 --> 00:27:07.750
You shouldn't do that.

277
00:27:09.540 --> 00:27:11.000
What we need…

278
00:27:11.040 --> 00:27:12.920
What <i>we</i>need?

279
00:27:12.960 --> 00:27:15.460
You, what you need.

280
00:27:16.170 --> 00:27:20.930
What you need is some kind of buffer
before depositing the money.


281
00:27:21.300 --> 00:27:22.760
A transit account.

282
00:27:23.260 --> 00:27:25.100
Otherwise, you're too exposed.

283
00:27:26.220 --> 00:27:30.890
Yeah, I know.
We'll have to look into it.


284
00:27:31.480 --> 00:27:35.150
And why Molton Trust as custodian?

285
00:27:35.690 --> 00:27:37.190
Get this:

286
00:27:37.230 --> 00:27:39.150
They have offices in Montreal.

287
00:27:39.190 --> 00:27:41.900
Customer service is in Toronto.

288
00:27:41.950 --> 00:27:46.580
Money transfers and banking operations
are in London,


289
00:27:46.620 --> 00:27:49.950
supervised by the parent company's
back office in Chicago.


290
00:27:50.000 --> 00:27:53.500
It's just about the most complex
organizational chart you can get.


291
00:27:53.920 --> 00:27:55.920
Hey, get your friend, will you?

292
00:27:59.880 --> 00:28:01.550
For financial statements?

293
00:28:01.590 --> 00:28:05.680
That's not a problem.
My accountant is very accommodating.


294
00:28:07.220 --> 00:28:10.480
Come on, Vincent, this is absurd.
Why should I approve this?


295
00:28:10.520 --> 00:28:12.140
Give me one good reason.

296
00:28:13.190 --> 00:28:16.270
I gave you 20,000, 
Denis, in small bills.

297
00:28:27.910 --> 00:28:29.490
See you soon.

298
00:28:31.120 --> 00:28:32.580
The question now, Éric,

299
00:28:32.620 --> 00:28:36.380
is would you rather hop on the train
and make some cash,


300
00:28:36.420 --> 00:28:39.090
or stay a small-time accountant
making $600 a week


301
00:28:39.130 --> 00:28:40.800
with your nose in our books?

302
00:28:42.420 --> 00:28:44.550
In January, I get my yearly bonus.

303
00:28:47.390 --> 00:28:50.970
After that, make me an offer.
We'll see.


304
00:29:01.780 --> 00:29:03.610
Thank you, Mr. Larrivée.

305
00:29:06.160 --> 00:29:07.320
Listen…

306
00:29:09.910 --> 00:29:14.040
I know my timing isn't great,
but I don't want to waste your time.


307
00:29:15.290 --> 00:29:16.830
I'm handing in my notice.

308
00:29:18.080 --> 00:29:20.130
What are you talking about, Éric?

309
00:29:20.750 --> 00:29:22.800
Sit. Let's talk.

310
00:29:23.630 --> 00:29:26.300
We can discuss your salary and benefits.

311
00:29:26.720 --> 00:29:28.800
I wasn't expecting this at all.

312
00:29:28.850 --> 00:29:29.930
I'm sorry.

313
00:29:30.390 --> 00:29:32.600
It's not you or the team.

314
00:29:33.430 --> 00:29:36.520
I feel like my time here is done.

315
00:29:36.560 --> 00:29:38.230
Come on!

316
00:29:41.270 --> 00:29:43.110
Who are we losing you to?

317
00:29:44.400 --> 00:29:47.860
I don't know yet.
I have a few prospects.


318
00:29:49.030 --> 00:29:51.410
You're kind of leaving us
in the lurch, Éric.


319
00:29:52.410 --> 00:29:56.410
But we can provide references
or letters of recommendation if you need.


320
00:29:56.460 --> 00:29:57.670
No thank you.

321
00:29:58.330 --> 00:30:00.040
That won't be necessary.

322
00:30:24.480 --> 00:30:27.400
Four years? OK.
You're good with the salary?


323
00:30:27.450 --> 00:30:32.120
Yes. But as I told you,
I'm more interested in the bonuses.


324
00:30:32.660 --> 00:30:35.870
Paid cash, when I see fit,
as an undeclared loan.


325
00:30:35.910 --> 00:30:38.080
Yeah, like we discussed.

326
00:30:42.040 --> 00:30:43.920
As for the signing bonus…

327
00:30:43.960 --> 00:30:45.460
$120,000, right?

328
00:30:46.050 --> 00:30:47.220
I'll write you a check.

329
00:30:47.260 --> 00:30:50.930
No, you should transfer the money
to your account,


330
00:30:50.970 --> 00:30:55.140
get a bank draft,
then write a personal check.


331
00:30:55.180 --> 00:30:57.520
Come on, Éric. Toughen up.

332
00:30:57.560 --> 00:30:59.940
You know the situation with Commission.

333
00:30:59.980 --> 00:31:02.020
I told you they're coming down on us.

334
00:31:02.060 --> 00:31:03.110
As you wish.

335
00:31:03.150 --> 00:31:06.650
I don't want my name in the books
with payments like that.


336
00:31:08.610 --> 00:31:10.200
How do I look?

337
00:32:21.980 --> 00:32:23.390
There you have it.

338
00:32:27.520 --> 00:32:30.690
$400,000, just like that?

339
00:32:31.190 --> 00:32:35.160
Just like that.
They never caught on.


340
00:32:35.200 --> 00:32:38.450
And because we write
our clients' account statements…


341
00:32:38.490 --> 00:32:39.950
I don't have to spell it out.

342
00:32:43.040 --> 00:32:46.210
It's the only way we can grow.
I don't see any other options.


343
00:32:47.670 --> 00:32:50.550
Yeah, but you'll have to return the cash.

344
00:32:50.590 --> 00:32:54.010
Of course!
It's all about timing.


345
00:32:54.050 --> 00:32:55.720
It's a poker game.

346
00:33:05.980 --> 00:33:08.690
OK, as most of you are aware,

347
00:33:08.730 --> 00:33:13.740
today, we're officially welcoming
our new VP of finance, Éric Asselin.


348
00:33:14.610 --> 00:33:15.660
Welcome!

349
00:33:17.490 --> 00:33:20.370
Éric will be starting immediately.

350
00:33:20.950 --> 00:33:23.120
So let's raise our glasses. Cheers!

351
00:33:23.160 --> 00:33:26.000
- Cheers!
- Welcome.


352
00:33:27.040 --> 00:33:28.210
Cheers, Éric.

353
00:33:29.750 --> 00:33:31.550
Well, thank you.

354
00:33:32.010 --> 00:33:35.300
Speeches aren't really my thing.
I'll leave that to Vincent.


355
00:33:36.010 --> 00:33:39.470
I just want to say
I'm happy to be here.


356
00:33:41.390 --> 00:33:42.640
Switzerland.

357
00:33:43.270 --> 00:33:47.230
I'd like to take a moment to tell you
about our new resolution for 2002:


358
00:33:47.270 --> 00:33:48.480
Switzerland.

359
00:33:48.520 --> 00:33:51.940
One-third of the world's wealth is there.

360
00:33:52.400 --> 00:33:56.780
An ambitious, growing firm like Norbourg
can't afford to miss out on that market.


361
00:33:56.820 --> 00:34:00.030
So 2002 will be the year of…

362
00:34:00.070 --> 00:34:01.410
Give me a hand.

363
00:34:04.790 --> 00:34:06.540
Eurobourg!

364
00:34:08.830 --> 00:34:10.960
Cheers!

365
00:34:15.550 --> 00:34:17.680
I know just the guy for Switzerland.

366
00:34:18.430 --> 00:34:23.310
He handles between $300 and $400 million,
and he's consul for an African country.


367
00:34:23.850 --> 00:34:25.430
- Oh yeah?
- Yeah.


368
00:34:25.480 --> 00:34:27.060
I went to school with his son.

369
00:34:27.770 --> 00:34:32.020
So why isn't he working for us yet?

370
00:34:52.960 --> 00:34:54.840
Vincent Lacroix…

371
00:34:59.780 --> 00:35:03.140
Our enviable positioning
in the North American market


372
00:35:03.180 --> 00:35:06.600
gives us a clear advantage
over other players.


373
00:35:06.640 --> 00:35:09.640
The acquisition of Tercio Trust
in the short term


374
00:35:09.690 --> 00:35:13.230
would put Eurobourg at the forefront
of the Swiss hedge fund world.


375
00:35:13.270 --> 00:35:17.740
As you see here,
the Tercio team would remain intact,


376
00:35:17.780 --> 00:35:21.240
and the transition to Eurobourg
would happen gradually.


377
00:37:33.580 --> 00:37:34.870
Vince!

378
00:37:38.380 --> 00:37:40.000
Don't send the fax yet!

379
00:37:41.170 --> 00:37:44.340
What are you doing?
That's the confirmation. The fax is sent.


380
00:37:44.380 --> 00:37:47.590
The USS01 account is $300,000 overdrawn.

381
00:37:47.640 --> 00:37:50.050
Fucking hell! You idiot!

382
00:37:50.100 --> 00:37:52.600
Do you know
the Molton Chicago number by heart?


383
00:38:16.040 --> 00:38:18.460
It's the transfer confirmation. Hang up!

384
00:38:21.130 --> 00:38:22.250
It worked.

385
00:38:22.300 --> 00:38:26.340
The account is $654,000 overdrawn now,
and they sent the money anyway.


386
00:38:26.380 --> 00:38:29.640
OK, how much do we have
in ULC02 and USS04?


387
00:38:29.680 --> 00:38:31.470
I'll have to check.

388
00:38:31.510 --> 00:38:32.720
We'll balance it.

389
00:38:57.710 --> 00:38:59.120
Thanks, Brigitte.

390
00:39:01.130 --> 00:39:02.840
You don't understand.

391
00:39:03.630 --> 00:39:06.130
A former colleague
at the Commission just told me


392
00:39:06.170 --> 00:39:08.510
the inspection is this fall, no way out.

393
00:39:08.550 --> 00:39:11.760
We'll just have to
make false bills and reports.


394
00:39:11.800 --> 00:39:13.260
We'll do better than that.

395
00:39:13.760 --> 00:39:15.600
We have to start thinking long-term.

396
00:39:15.640 --> 00:39:18.730
The safest way is to declare revenue
from external companies.


397
00:39:18.770 --> 00:39:22.060
The Tercio Trust subsidiaries
in Switzerland are our best bet.


398
00:39:22.110 --> 00:39:25.280
That's good, Vincent.
We own Tercio.


399
00:39:25.320 --> 00:39:29.700
We control the archives, books
and financial statements from past years.


400
00:39:29.740 --> 00:39:32.070
We all know there's a firewall
for Switzerland.


401
00:39:32.120 --> 00:39:35.160
We twist things right,
it'll be hard for the Commission.


402
00:39:35.200 --> 00:39:37.910
They don't have the jurisdiction
or the staff.


403
00:39:37.950 --> 00:39:39.250
I'll take the lead on this.

404
00:39:39.290 --> 00:39:42.250
I know what they're looking for
and how they work.


405
00:39:42.290 --> 00:39:44.340
I know how they think. Trust me.

406
00:39:44.960 --> 00:39:47.050
So let's get to work.
Serficom is ready?


407
00:39:47.090 --> 00:39:48.550
Yes, it's settled.

408
00:39:49.970 --> 00:39:51.630
We'll need more.

409
00:39:53.260 --> 00:39:57.233
The purchase agreements
for Moulty Bay Holdings and Grace Venture?


410
00:39:57.286 --> 00:39:59.850
No shells or shady offshore dealings.

411
00:39:59.890 --> 00:40:01.890
You give them those,
it opens a breach.


412
00:40:03.690 --> 00:40:06.770
Éric, I'll let you handle it
if you know what you're doing.


413
00:40:06.820 --> 00:40:09.280
Yeah, I'm pretty sure
I know what I'm doing.


414
00:40:10.650 --> 00:40:13.950
I'm also pretty sure we'll need help.

415
00:40:13.990 --> 00:40:17.120
We're taking a massive beating
with the hedge funds.


416
00:40:33.720 --> 00:40:35.260
Hello, hello!

417
00:40:36.760 --> 00:40:38.680
- Welcome to Norbourg.
- Hello.


418
00:40:38.720 --> 00:40:41.020
I'm Vincent, CEO.

419
00:40:41.640 --> 00:40:46.150
Our new vice president-general manager,
Jean-Marie Davila. A big fish.


420
00:40:46.190 --> 00:40:47.570
- Nice to meet you.
- Hello.


421
00:40:47.610 --> 00:40:49.070
Seven years at the Caisse,

422
00:40:49.110 --> 00:40:52.950
three at the FTQ
and two years at BNP Paribas in Paris.


423
00:40:52.990 --> 00:40:56.320
I'm sure we'll have time
to discuss his resumé later.


424
00:40:56.910 --> 00:41:00.120
Would you like a coffee before starting?

425
00:41:00.160 --> 00:41:01.830
Where should we set up?

426
00:41:02.370 --> 00:41:03.750
Follow me.

427
00:41:04.420 --> 00:41:08.000
If you need any documents, just ask,
and we'll get them.


428
00:41:08.040 --> 00:41:11.260
Yes, that's how an inspection
usually works.


429
00:41:11.300 --> 00:41:16.140
And you'll be in familiar territory
with an expert who needs no introduction.


430
00:41:17.260 --> 00:41:19.850
Anne
-Marie, Guy…

431
00:41:20.560 --> 00:41:21.680
Ah, René.

432
00:41:24.230 --> 00:41:25.310
Good to see you.

433
00:41:30.190 --> 00:41:33.570
Come on, Éric, do we really have to
do this with you?


434
00:41:43.540 --> 00:41:46.710
Well, why not? 
Let's do this.

435
00:41:47.460 --> 00:41:49.590
OK, let's start with compliance.

436
00:41:49.630 --> 00:41:52.300
We want to see the company's
organizational chart


437
00:41:52.340 --> 00:41:54.630
and all the certificates of incorporation.

438
00:41:55.050 --> 00:41:57.590
No problem. I'll explain all that to you.

439
00:41:58.430 --> 00:41:59.970
I'm leaving you in good hands.

440
00:42:00.010 --> 00:42:02.430
If you need anything, 
I'm right next door.

441
00:42:02.470 --> 00:42:03.890
Thank you, Vincent.

442
00:42:06.190 --> 00:42:09.190
This won't work, Éric.
We can't do this.


443
00:42:09.230 --> 00:42:12.400
You're the one that started
the Norbourg investigation.


444
00:42:17.233 --> 00:42:20.410
Why don't you designate
someone else as our contact?


445
00:42:20.450 --> 00:42:21.620
Yeah.

446
00:42:27.870 --> 00:42:31.420
This is the most ridiculous situation
I've ever been in.


447
00:42:31.880 --> 00:42:35.340
Seriously, Éric,
you could have spared us this farce.


448
00:42:35.380 --> 00:42:37.220
We'll start with the parent company?

449
00:42:37.260 --> 00:42:40.640
Yes, we have some questions
about the shareholders.


450
00:42:42.510 --> 00:42:44.020
I'm listening.

451
00:42:46.560 --> 00:42:49.440
The VLX from March 2000 is missing.

452
00:42:50.560 --> 00:42:54.280
How do you explain
the $150,000 difference in amortization?


453
00:42:56.190 --> 00:42:57.530
<i>I don't understand, Éric.</i>

454
00:42:57.570 --> 00:43:01.530
The private management mandates
for Dubrovsky, Ranhold and Robertson


455
00:43:01.570 --> 00:43:05.120
are with a broker who trades
in derivative products.


456
00:43:05.160 --> 00:43:07.460
Is that what you're telling me?

457
00:43:07.870 --> 00:43:11.580
And these amounts here… Thank you.

458
00:43:11.630 --> 00:43:16.130
Why are they in "Vincent Lacroix Advances."
What is that?


459
00:43:16.920 --> 00:43:18.550
Let me have a look.

460
00:43:20.760 --> 00:43:23.600
Yeah, I don't know.
Must be in the archives.


461
00:43:25.010 --> 00:43:29.940
The report must be in my files at home.
I think that's it.


462
00:43:31.770 --> 00:43:35.530
That must be at the accountant's office
in La Prairie, right, Vincent?


463
00:43:35.570 --> 00:43:37.570
That's it. Don't worry.

464
00:43:37.610 --> 00:43:40.820
We'll get you all the documents
by tomorrow.


465
00:43:52.920 --> 00:43:54.250
Have a good evening.

466
00:43:55.210 --> 00:43:56.300
Thanks for coming.

467
00:43:56.340 --> 00:43:57.760
See you tomorrow.

468
00:44:03.050 --> 00:44:04.470
Fuck.

469
00:44:07.970 --> 00:44:09.560
Starting now,

470
00:44:10.060 --> 00:44:12.600
extra entertainment expenses
will be cash.


471
00:44:12.650 --> 00:44:14.980
They're staying out of our books.
Is that clear?


472
00:44:15.020 --> 00:44:17.820
Don't worry.
They don't have anything on us yet.


473
00:44:18.440 --> 00:44:20.650
So, you have the list to produce?

474
00:44:20.700 --> 00:44:24.410
Yeah. Another night shift for us.

475
00:45:59.210 --> 00:46:01.420
- That'll hit the spot.
- Thanks.


476
00:46:14.230 --> 00:46:15.940
It's gonna be fine.

477
00:46:15.980 --> 00:46:17.150
Here we go again.

478
00:46:21.020 --> 00:46:22.280
Welcome back!

479
00:46:22.320 --> 00:46:24.030
- Hello.
- Have a seat.


480
00:46:25.320 --> 00:46:29.070
Today, Éric, I want to
talk about the custodians,


481
00:46:29.120 --> 00:46:33.080
so Investpro TD,
but especially Molton Trust.


482
00:46:33.620 --> 00:46:37.250
We have questions about
the way Molton Trust documents


483
00:46:37.290 --> 00:46:38.790
regarding the funds' value

484
00:46:38.830 --> 00:46:41.290
are sent to Norbourg.

485
00:46:41.340 --> 00:46:44.210
- Oh yeah?
- There seem to be different procedures.


486
00:46:44.260 --> 00:46:47.840
That's because their
Montreal offices closed,


487
00:46:47.880 --> 00:46:50.850
and we changed intermediaries
along the way.


488
00:46:50.890 --> 00:46:53.890
OK, well, we just want
supporting documentation.


489
00:46:54.680 --> 00:46:56.230
For what period?

490
00:46:56.680 --> 00:46:58.480
Today is October 1?

491
00:46:58.520 --> 00:47:03.110
Then the account statements from October 1
for 1999, 2000 and 2001.


492
00:47:04.110 --> 00:47:06.530
OK, we'll get them for you.

493
00:47:06.570 --> 00:47:09.450
So you're gonna bring
us a piece of paper?

494
00:47:10.320 --> 00:47:11.620
What will that prove?

495
00:47:11.660 --> 00:47:14.290
There's not much more
we can do, Anne-Marie.


496
00:47:14.330 --> 00:47:16.790
We could find the originals.

497
00:47:16.830 --> 00:47:19.170
But those are in the archives too, right?

498
00:47:19.210 --> 00:47:21.580
Yeah, and we'd need to
search the old database,


499
00:47:21.630 --> 00:47:22.840
and our head IT guy is…

500
00:47:22.880 --> 00:47:25.800
He's been out sick. We know.

501
00:47:39.980 --> 00:47:42.020
Everything OK here?

